# TypeScript Patterns

## No `any`

Use `unknown` with type guards or explicit casts. `any` bypasses type checking and hides real bugs.

## Dynamic key access on typed objects

When accessing a typed interface with a computed string key (e.g. model portfolio asset class fields), use the double cast to document that the unsafe access is intentional:

```ts
// ✅ correct — makes intent explicit
const mp = modelPortfolio as unknown as Record<string, unknown>
const target = mp[`${key}_target`] as number | null

// ❌ TypeScript rejects this direct cast
const mp = modelPortfolio as Record<string, unknown>
```

## Display formatting

Use helpers from `lib/formatters`. Never format numbers inline.

```ts
import { fmtDecimalPct, fmtNum, fmtInt, EMPTY } from '@/lib/formatters'

fmtDecimalPct(value)   // 0.0831 → "8.31%"
fmtNum(value)          // 1.234 → "1.23"
fmtInt(value)          // 42.7 → "43"
EMPTY                  // '—' — always use for null/missing display values, never hardcode '—'
```

## Null guards before navigation

```ts
// ✅ safe
onClick={() => { if (id != null) navigate(`/security/${id}`) }}

// ❌ navigates to the literal string "/security/null"
onClick={() => navigate(`/security/${id}`)}
```

## Strict mode is enabled

Both `noUnusedLocals` and `noUnusedParameters` are on. If you add a parameter or variable, use it or remove it. The build will fail otherwise.

## Path aliases

Use `@/` for imports from `src/`:
```ts
import { supabase } from '@/lib/supabase'     // ✅
import { supabase } from '../../lib/supabase' // ❌
```

## Component file structure

- `lib/*.ts` — pure async Supabase functions + TypeScript types for that domain
- `hooks/*.ts` — `useQuery`/`useMutation` wrappers; import from lib
- `components/*.tsx` — UI only; accept props, call hooks, no direct Supabase
- `pages/*.tsx` — route-level; own URL params, compose components

Keep business logic in `lib/`, not in components or pages.
